# Git-style commits and comments

When proposing **git commit messages**, **PR descriptions**, or short **change summaries**, follow the conventions Git recommends for contributors.

## Commit subject (first line)

- Use **imperative mood**, as if completing: `Add login`, `Fix null reference`, `Refactor todo service` (not past tense: ~~Added~~, ~~Fixed~~).
- **Capitalize** the first word after any type prefix (if you use Conventional Commits, keep it consistent, e.g. `feat: Add JWT auth`).
- Keep the subject **short** (aim **≤ 50 characters**; hard limit **≤ 72** if needed).
- **No period** at the end of the subject line.
- One logical change per commit message; if mixed, split the suggestion into separate commits.

## Commit body (optional, when more detail is needed)

- Leave **one blank line** between subject and body.
- Wrap body lines at **~72 characters**.
- Explain **what** changed and **why**, not implementation trivia unless it prevents regressions.

## Examples

```text
Add FluentValidation for auth DTOs

Register validators in DI and return consistent 400 responses
for invalid register/login payloads.
```

```text
Fix todo ownership check on PATCH status
```

## Code comments (when you add them)

- Prefer **short, imperative** phrases that explain **why** or non-obvious **invariants**, not narration of the code.
- Match the existing file’s language for comments (English vs Persian) unless the user asks otherwise.
